summary: With One Push 8
title: With One Push 8
body:
Pairing: Peter Parker x Reader

Warnings: Language. Angst. Sibling taunting. Sick kids. Rotten Ex. Grieving. Arguing. Hot and Cold reactions.

   After too many blind dates that were so bad, you felt sanitary showers were needed after, you’d given up on dating.
Who had the time with a career as a doctor?
Till you have his daughter getting stitches on your table.
He’s gorgeous, and surely married? No ring? Gay? No not with the way his eyes are raking over you.
No, he couldn’t be interested in you, your luck was never that good.
Right?
Widowed, he thought the only love he’d have was for his daughter Mae.
But she wants a mom, needs a mom.
With the help of his adoptive brother and father, Peter strikes out into the dating world.
Bad date, after bad date, leaves him not holding out hope.
One fall and five stitches from the most attractive and sweet doctor?
His luck couldn’t be that good.
Could it?

Tag List Is Open!! If you are crossed out, please check your settings. I will remove you after so long!!

“Here Mrs. Barton.” Peter hands her the To Go Cup of tea.

“Peter, you’re a sweetheart. Thank you.” She smiles at him.

“Y/N took good care of Mae while she was in here. So, I can only repay the favor.” He smiles at her.

“You have a kid?” A male voice makes him look up. Clint is looking at him.

“The sweetest little girl, Mae.” Karen gushes. “Just too damn cute that one.” She pats his hand before walking away.

“I have a daughter. She’s about to be five.” He nods.

“I have a five year old myself. She’s Nicole.” Clint nods. “We weren’t properly introduced. Clint Barton.” He puts his hand out.

“Peter Parker.” He shakes Clint’s hand.

“Parker? Like Stark and Parker?” Clint stares at him.

“Yes. That’s my family.” He nods.

“Wow. Wow.” He nods almost in shock. “They say high society people suck, but you can’t be that bad if my mom and sister think you’re pretty great.” He chuckles.

“I don’t think they know.” He nods. “I mean they’ve never asked.” He shrugs.

“Well I can understand. Dating with your um name and company. Has to be hard. I’ll keep it to myself.” Clint nods.

“It’s not a secret. I don’t find your sister to be a gold digger.” He chuckles. “Though she might like my daughter more than me.” He smirks.

“She’s a good girl. Mean as hell to me, but everyone else loves her.” He smiles softly. “She’s had some bad luck dating, so don’t hold it against her if she’s a little hesitant with you.” Clint nods. “But the woman is a damn saint. Don’t ever tell her I said that, but she’s probably the best person I know, aside from my wife.” He chuckles.

“Mae, my daughter is obsessed with her already.” He chuckles.

“Oh you have no idea. My girl’s all about her aunt.” He smirks.

“Clint?” Laura moves towards him, her one hand on her belly, the other hand holds a clip board and pen.

“Insurance?” Clint swallows.

“I don’t know what to fill out.” She sighs.

“I’ll look it over.” Clint nods.

“Y/N said you have your own business?” Peter looks at him.

“Construction company. Things are a little slow right now.” He nods looking at the clipboard his wife had given him.

“What construction do you do?” Peter asks.

“Really anything.” He chuckles. “My wife says there isn’t anything I can’t build, which I guess is true.” He smirks.

“We’re looking for a new construction company for the company. My dads ridiculously picky, and my mom’s been talking about wanting to redo part of the tower.” Peter shrugs. “Got a card?” He smiles at Clint.

“Are you kidding me?” Clint looks almost shocked.

“No. Y/N’s mentioned how dedicated and hard working you are. If things are slow, I’d gladly give you the business.” He chuckles.

“I’d kill for a bid like that.” Clint grins wide.

“I’ll talk to my father in the morning. Promise.” Peter takes the card Clint is pulling out of his wallet. “I need to check when my daughters checkup is, I’ll be right back.” He stands up from the chair heading for the nurses’ station.

“Callum Barton.” He smiles at the nurse.

“Yes, how can I help you?” She nods.

“I’d like to pay his hospital bill.” He nods, pulling out his wallet and slipping his black card into her hand.

“Of course Sir. Should I print you a receipt?” She smiles.

“No thank you.” He shakes his head.

He’s signing the papers when Y/N comes out. Looking at him funny, he quickly slips everything back to the nurse and meets her half way.

“What were you doing?” She squints at him.

“I forgot to sign a few things when I was here with Mae.” He chuckles.

“You’re a very bad liar.” She grins at him.

“Shhh. You don’t need to tell people.” He grins at her.

“Let me talk to my brother and you can take me home?” She grins at him.

“Hungry?” He smiles at her.

“Starving.” She laughs.

“I know a really great 24/7 diner.” He winks leading her over to her family.



“Okay, so Clint you have to stay awake with him tonight. Can you do that?” You ask him.

“I’ll make the coffee when we get home.” Laura nods.

“I’ll call if I have any issues.” Clint smiles at you.

“I’ll handle your bill.” You walk away before anyone can say anything. “The bill for Callum Barton. Please?” You smile at the nurse. She looks at you confused.

“The gentleman you are with already handled it.” She explains.

“What?” You blink at her.

“The man you arrived with.” She nods. You turn looking at Peter talking to your family, his hands in his pockets a small smirk plays on his lips.

“Thank you.” You walk away.

“Do you need anything from us?” Laura asks quickly.

“No.” You stare at Peter, who was struggling like he didn’t know whether to grin or move away from you.

“What’s wrong?” Clint looks at you.

“He paid Callum’s bill.” You continue to stare at Peter, your family turns looking at him.

“I did.” He nods, a small smile on his lips.

“What?!” Your mom and Laura gasp at the same time.

“Why?” You fold your arms over your chest.

“Because you took care of my baby. It’s called paying it forward.” He grins at you.

“I stitched your baby up, I didn’t pay her medical bill. Peter you have to let me pay you back.” You shake your head.

“Nope. But you can just say thank you and let me ask if your family wants to join us for something to eat.” He smirks.

“Oh no you did enough already.” Your mom shakes her head.

“I don’t even know what to say right now.” Clint looks from you to Peter.

“Thank you.” Laura is already welling up with tears as she hugs Peter awkwardly due to her bump. “Sorry hormones.” She wipes at her eyes.

“My pleasure. Thanks for not kicking my ass for dating your sister.” Peter grins at Clint.

“Oh god, we’re leaving, before they start bonding and embarrassing stories start getting shared.” You groan, you grab Peter’s hand, blowing kisses to your family and head for the main doors.

“Embarrassing stories, huh?” Peter grins.

“Dating huh?” You grin at him. He pulls the car door open kissing you quickly before you get in.

“I’ll make the coffee when we get home.” Laura nods.

“I’ll call if I have any issues.” Clint smiles at you.

“I’ll handle your bill.” You walk away before anyone can say anything. “The bill for Callum Barton. Please?” You smile at the nurse. She looks at you confused.

“The gentleman you are with already handled it.” She explains.

“What?” You blink at her.

“The man you arrived with.” She nods. You turn looking at Peter talking to your family, his hands in his pockets a small smirk plays on his lips.

“Thank you.” You walk away.

“Do you need anything from us?” Laura asks quickly.

“No.” You stare at Peter, who was struggling like he didn’t know whether to grin or move away from you.

“What’s wrong?” Clint looks at you.

“He paid Callum’s bill.” You continue to stare at Peter, your family turns looking at him.

“I did.” He nods, a small smile on his lips.

“What?!” Your mom and Laura gasp at the same time.

“Why?” You fold your arms over your chest.

“Because you took care of my baby. It’s called paying it forward.” He grins at you.

“I stitched your baby up, I didn’t pay her medical bill. Peter you have to let me pay you back.” You shake your head.

“Nope. But you can just say thank you and let me ask if your family wants to join us for something to eat.” He smirks.

“Oh no you did enough already.” Your mom shakes her head.

“I don’t even know what to say right now.” Clint looks from you to Peter.

“Thank you.” Laura is already welling up with tears as she hugs Peter awkwardly due to her bump. “Sorry hormones.” She wipes at her eyes.

“My pleasure. Thanks for not kicking my ass for dating your sister.” Peter grins at Clint.

“Oh god, we’re leaving, before they start bonding and embarrassing stories start getting shared.” You groan, you grab Peter’s hand, blowing kisses to your family and head for the main doors.

“Embarrassing stories, huh?” Peter grins.

“Dating huh?” You grin at him. He pulls the car door open kissing you quickly before you get in.

Pairing: Peter Parker x Reader

Warnings: Language. Angst. Sibling taunting. Sick kids. Rotten Ex. Grieving. Arguing. Hot and Cold reactions.

   After too many blind dates that were so bad, you felt sanitary showers were needed after, you’d given up on dating.
Who had the time with a career as a doctor?
Till you have his daughter getting stitches on your table.
He’s gorgeous, and surely married? No ring? Gay? No not with the way his eyes are raking over you.
No, he couldn’t be interested in you, your luck was never that good.
Right?
Widowed, he thought the only love he’d have was for his daughter Mae.
But she wants a mom, needs a mom.
With the help of his adoptive brother and father, Peter strikes out into the dating world.
Bad date, after bad date, leaves him not holding out hope.
One fall and five stitches from the most attractive and sweet doctor?
His luck couldn’t be that good.
Could it?

“Here Mrs. Barton.” Peter hands her the To Go Cup of tea.

“Peter, you’re a sweetheart. Thank you.” She smiles at him.

“Y/N took good care of Mae while she was in here. So, I can only repay the favor.” He smiles at her.

“You have a kid?” A male voice makes him look up. Clint is looking at him.

“The sweetest little girl, Mae.” Karen gushes. “Just too damn cute that one.” She pats his hand before walking away.

“I have a daughter. She’s about to be five.” He nods.

“I have a five year old myself. She’s Nicole.” Clint nods. “We weren’t properly introduced. Clint Barton.” He puts his hand out.

“Peter Parker.” He shakes Clint’s hand.

“Parker? Like Stark and Parker?” Clint stares at him.

“Yes. That’s my family.” He nods.

“Wow. Wow.” He nods almost in shock. “They say high society people suck, but you can’t be that bad if my mom and sister think you’re pretty great.” He chuckles.

“I don’t think they know.” He nods. “I mean they’ve never asked.” He shrugs.

“Well I can understand. Dating with your um name and company. Has to be hard. I’ll keep it to myself.” Clint nods.

“It’s not a secret. I don’t find your sister to be a gold digger.” He chuckles. “Though she might like my daughter more than me.” He smirks.

“She’s a good girl. Mean as hell to me, but everyone else loves her.” He smiles softly. “She’s had some bad luck dating, so don’t hold it against her if she’s a little hesitant with you.” Clint nods. “But the woman is a damn saint. Don’t ever tell her I said that, but she’s probably the best person I know, aside from my wife.” He chuckles.

“Mae, my daughter is obsessed with her already.” He chuckles.

“Oh you have no idea. My girl’s all about her aunt.” He smirks.

“Clint?” Laura moves towards him, her one hand on her belly, the other hand holds a clip board and pen.

“Insurance?” Clint swallows.

“I don’t know what to fill out.” She sighs.

“I’ll look it over.” Clint nods.

“Y/N said you have your own business?” Peter looks at him.

“Construction company. Things are a little slow right now.” He nods looking at the clipboard his wife had given him.

“What construction do you do?” Peter asks.

“Really anything.” He chuckles. “My wife says there isn’t anything I can’t build, which I guess is true.” He smirks.

“We’re looking for a new construction company for the company. My dads ridiculously picky, and my mom’s been talking about wanting to redo part of the tower.” Peter shrugs. “Got a card?” He smiles at Clint.

“Are you kidding me?” Clint looks almost shocked.

“No. Y/N’s mentioned how dedicated and hard working you are. If things are slow, I’d gladly give you the business.” He chuckles.

“I’d kill for a bid like that.” Clint grins wide.

“I’ll talk to my father in the morning. Promise.” Peter takes the card Clint is pulling out of his wallet. “I need to check when my daughters checkup is, I’ll be right back.” He stands up from the chair heading for the nurses’ station.

“Callum Barton.” He smiles at the nurse.

“Yes, how can I help you?” She nods.

“I’d like to pay his hospital bill.” He nods, pulling out his wallet and slipping his black card into her hand.

“Of course Sir. Should I print you a receipt?” She smiles.

“No thank you.” He shakes his head.

He’s signing the papers when Y/N comes out. Looking at him funny, he quickly slips everything back to the nurse and meets her half way.

“What were you doing?” She squints at him.

“I forgot to sign a few things when I was here with Mae.” He chuckles.

“You’re a very bad liar.” She grins at him.

“Shhh. You don’t need to tell people.” He grins at her.

“Let me talk to my brother and you can take me home?” She grins at him.

“Hungry?” He smiles at her.

“Starving.” She laughs.

“I know a really great 24/7 diner.” He winks leading her over to her family.



“Okay, so Clint you have to stay awake with him tonight. Can you do that?” You ask him.

“I’ll make the coffee when we get home.” Laura nods.

“I’ll call if I have any issues.” Clint smiles at you.

“I’ll handle your bill.” You walk away before anyone can say anything. “The bill for Callum Barton. Please?” You smile at the nurse. She looks at you confused.

“The gentleman you are with already handled it.” She explains.

“What?” You blink at her.

“The man you arrived with.” She nods. You turn looking at Peter talking to your family, his hands in his pockets a small smirk plays on his lips.

“Thank you.” You walk away.

“Do you need anything from us?” Laura asks quickly.

“No.” You stare at Peter, who was struggling like he didn’t know whether to grin or move away from you.

“What’s wrong?” Clint looks at you.

“He paid Callum’s bill.” You continue to stare at Peter, your family turns looking at him.

“I did.” He nods, a small smile on his lips.

“What?!” Your mom and Laura gasp at the same time.

“Why?” You fold your arms over your chest.

“Because you took care of my baby. It’s called paying it forward.” He grins at you.

“I stitched your baby up, I didn’t pay her medical bill. Peter you have to let me pay you back.” You shake your head.

“Nope. But you can just say thank you and let me ask if your family wants to join us for something to eat.” He smirks.

“Oh no you did enough already.” Your mom shakes her head.

“I don’t even know what to say right now.” Clint looks from you to Peter.

“Thank you.” Laura is already welling up with tears as she hugs Peter awkwardly due to her bump. “Sorry hormones.” She wipes at her eyes.

“My pleasure. Thanks for not kicking my ass for dating your sister.” Peter grins at Clint.

“Oh god, we’re leaving, before they start bonding and embarrassing stories start getting shared.” You groan, you grab Peter’s hand, blowing kisses to your family and head for the main doors.

“Embarrassing stories, huh?” Peter grins.

“Dating huh?” You grin at him. He pulls the car door open kissing you quickly before you get in.
